Europe
------
[1] The Netherlands (Bible Belt)
Date: Sat 20 Jul 2013
Source: El Pais [In Spanish, machine trans., summ., edited]
http://sociedad.elpais.com/sociedad/2013/07/20/actualidad/1374334055_000414.html


A measles epidemic has broken out in the so-called Bible Belt encompassing a Dutch Calvinist majority area that crosses the country from west to east. The population of the Bible Belt refuse vaccines on the basis of their religious convictions, and this has fuelled a national debate on the rights of the child. Or rather, on the right of the state to force parents to protect their children from preventable infectious diseases. The official number of children at risk is 466, but according to the National Institute of Public Health (RIVM) it may be 10 times higher. "In this community, not everyone goes to the doctor or informs the relevant health authorities," say Dutch virologists, who have launched an urgent campaign to inoculate 6000 at-risk babies between 6 and 14 months old. "The campaign is designated an invitation, because nationwide the vaccination schedule is voluntary. In practice, the aim is to cover more than 95 per cent of the population to eliminate the disease. Vaccination is offered where less than 90 per cent of the population has been vaccinated," they added. Between 1999 and 2000, 3 children died of measles in a similar episode and 150 were hospitalized.

The [MMR] vaccine provides protection against measles, mumps and rubella. However, the hard core of Dutch Calvinists numbers about 600 000 and this group has 3 seats in the Dutch Parliament of 150 members; a vigorous debate is being conducted at this level. Their creed leads them to question the scientific evidence favouring vaccination. Some, however, admit that peer pressure has led them to decline vaccination for their children. Aware of this situation, the RIVM has ensured that the recommendations are delivered directly to private addresses. The political debate continues unresolved [Readers interested in the arguments of the Calvinists should access the original text via the source URL. - Mod.CP].

Overall, there have been 2 cases of encephalitis and 2 pneumonias; 5 more, and an infant, are seriously ill. In 1971, the same biblical dogma was instrumental in the emergence of a poliomyelitis epidemic that killed 5 children and left another 44 with serious sequelae [pathological conditions resulting from the disease]. In 1999 there was a 2nd such outbreak.

[byline: Isabel Ferrer]

--
