[2] Russia (Moscow region)
Date: Thu 18 Jul 2013
Source: Inmosreg.ru [In Russian, trans. Mod.CP, edited]
http://inmosreg.ru/happen_news_society/20130718/600574464.html


The incidence of measles has increased 1.4-fold in the suburbs of Moscow during the 1st half of 2013 compared with the same period in the previous year. 95 per cent of measles patients either had not been vaccinated against the disease or had no record of vaccination, according to a statement from the Moscow Region Rospotrebnadzor [Health and Welfare Administration].

"During the 1st 6 months of 2013 a total of 136 cases of measles was recorded -- a 1.4-fold increase in incidence, amounting to 1.98 cases per 100 000 population. Infants were the predominant age group affected comprising 56.6 per cent (77 individuals), and the adult population 43.4 per cent (59 people)," according to the statement.

Outbreaks of measles were recorded in the Mytishchi, Odintsovskom, Balashikhinsky, Istra, Resurrection, Lenin, Ramenskoye Schelkovskoy, Pushkin, Ljuberetsky, and Naro-Fominsk areas, and specifically in the adjacent Litkarino, Jubilee, Khimki, Dolgoprudnom, and Chekhov districts.

In 2012, the incidence of measles increased several fold in Moscow, with about 100 cases. Measles is an acute infectious viral disease that is rapidly transmitted from person to person, even during brief or limited contact with the patient. It is easy to become infected through contact with children [prior to vaccination] and adults who have not been immunised against measles virus infection. A sick person is contagious until 5 days after the start of a visible rash on the skin and mucous membranes. The illness usually lasts 10-15 days, deaths occurring only in complicated cases in infants and the elderly.

