Africa
------
[3] Congo DR (Katanga)
Date: Fri 19 Jul 2013
Source: Radio Okapi [In French, machine trans., edited]
http://radiookapi.net/actualite/2013/07/19/katanga-la-rougeole-fait-48-deces-depuis-janvier-selon-ocha/


About 48 people have died as a result of measles virus infection and over 3000 cases have been reported since January [2013] in Katanga province. The report of the Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA), published on Wed 17 Jul 2012 in Lubumbashi, states that the territories of Kabalo and Kalemie in Tanganyika district have been the most affected by this disease.

Tanganyika Health District alone has recorded 1511 cases of measles, including 14 deaths. This is an area of Luanika Kalemie territory, inhabited mostly by pygmies, and remains the most affected part of the health district. According to information collected by the 4 provincial health authorities in of Katanga, quoted by the OCHA, the extent of the disease is beyond the capacity of the local authorities responsible for containing the outbreak.

The rise of the epidemic is mainly due to low immunization coverage in many health zones in the province of Katanga and poor allocation of funds for the organization of immunization campaigns. Several sources indicate that the Kalemie health zone, for example, has provided no known response to the vaccination campaign against measles in a year. Medecins Sans Frontieres (MSF), which helps handle cases of measles in Luanika [Bas-Congo province], is faced with logistical problems. The World Health Organization (WHO), quoted by OCHA, says that the need for the organization of immunization activities is enormous in Katanga.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
