[7] USA (New York)
Date: Mon 22 Jul 2013
Source: The Jewish Daily Forward [edited]
http://forward.com/articles/180965/new-york-measles-outbreak-halted-among-orthodox/


A measles outbreak among New York's Orthodox Jewish community has been curtailed, according to officials for the New York City's Department of Health. From March to June [2013], 58 cases of measles were reported in Williamsburg and Boro Park in Brooklyn, 2 heavily populated Orthodox Jewish communities, among children and adults who were not vaccinated or had denied vaccination. The Department of Health and Mental Hygiene (DOHMH) worked with yeshivas, rabbis, and other community groups to report cases and encourage vaccination.

The outbreak resulted in one case of pneumonia and 2 hospitalizations. Measles is a viral infection that can also cause miscarriages, brain inflammation, hospitalization, and even death. The collaboration between city health officials and the Orthodox community on measles prevention was notably more cooperative than other recent efforts between the 2 parties. Members of the ultra-Orthodox Jewish community and the DOHMH are currently involved in litigation revolving around the city's regulation of metzitzah b'peh [MBP], a controversial oral suction cleansing technique used after circumcision, which can transmit herpes. Pro-MBP advocates claim the city's medical evidence is false and that the regulation infringes on religious rights.

[byline: Seth Berkman]

